Professor of Theology in 1515 and Ordinary Professor 111 1520 z holding therewith the annexed canoni-ies in St. Peter's church. In 1516 he was D.D. 3 and just at this time, for the half-year 31 Aug. 1520—28 Feb. 1521, he was Rector of the University. In 1524, on the foundation of the College du Pape, he was appointed its first President ; and in 1525 he was one of the judges to try John Pistorius, the first Dutch martyr of the Reformation. Between 1516—19 he composed many devotional works, which had a wide popular circulation3 all except one being in Dutch. They were printed at Antwerp, mostly by Hillen (Ep. 1053. 13311). See BN., with a very careful bibliography ; and de Jongh, pp. 165—7. Apart from the present appeal to him as Rector (cf. Epp. 1164, 1172) Erasmus had not much to do with him ; but he speaks of him later with praise (Lond. xix. 13, LB. 862: 17 May 1527). The year-date of this letter is confirmed by Rosemondt's tenure of the Rectorship. It can scarcely be doubted that the letter was 111 the hands of the author of the Acta Acczcl. Louanc'ensis (ef. Ep. 1195. 4n).]
